[1]
Date: Wed 26 Oct 2016
Source: Florida Keys News [edited]
http://www.flkeysnews.com/news/local/environment/article110523562.html


Key deer deaths slowing down
----------------------------
Finally, good news for the endangered Key deer: The number of deer found to be infected with New World screwworm on Big Pine Key and No Name Key is slowly going down, along with the number of those having to be euthanized. Kevin Lowry, chief public information officer with the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service at the National Key Deer Refuge, said even though the parasitic screwworm larvae have caused the deaths of 114 Key deer, none had to be euthanized Tuesday [25 Oct 2016].

He said officials are optimistic the numbers will continue to come down, preserving the Key deer population, which was estimated at about 1000 before the deaths and euthanizations of infected deer began in July [2016]. The deer, just 3 feet high, are found only in the Florida Keys and are on the Endangered Species List.

Asked about the possibility of moving some Key deer off the refuge to save them, he said translocating some could be considered in preservation efforts but nothing has been confirmed. "The main thing we want to do is keep them here and not remove them," he said. "The population could become stable here quickly. It's a very good sign to have zero deer euthanized for the latest report and it's all about making sure they remain in their native environment."

Lowry said the number is dropping due to the efforts of refuge officers and the help of 120 volunteers on Big Pine and No Name who are treating deer with doramectin, an antiparasitic medicine that serves as a preventive measure and treatment for screwworm. Initial treatments began last week. After receiving a dose of doramectin on a piece of bread, the deer are marked with nontoxic paint in a specific color for the day they're treated to tell refuge staff those deer were treated.

"We have developed neighborhood strike teams, so when the volunteers are properly trained, we're identifying neighborhoods and they're being labeled to that area," Lowry said. "Then they report to pick up supplies and materials and are charged with reporting back the number of deer they've treated."

Screwworm flies lay their eggs in open wounds where larvae hatch and feed, basically eating the deer alive. Many of the deer wounds are believed to come from rutting -- males battling each other for mates. So far, 259 females and 176 males have been treated with doramectin.

Sterile male screwworms continue to be released to mate with female flies as well, a successful method to kill the population created by the U.S. Department of Agriculture in the 1960s.

Dr. Doug Mader, veterinarian and owner of the Marathon Veterinary Hospital, said pet owners should check their pets twice a day. He has seen 2 pigs, 1 cat and 1 dog put down because of the screwworm and said owners shouldn't wait to take their animal to a veterinarian if they see signs of screwworm. As of Tuesday [25 Oct 2016], state Department of Agriculture and Consumer Services law enforcement officers have inspected 1644 animals heading out of the Keys at an inspection point at mile marker 106 in Key Largo and found no instances of the screwworm fly.

Those interested in volunteering to treat Key deer should email Kristie Killam, refuge park ranger, at keydeer@fws.gov. To report an infected deer, call (305) 470-6863, Ext. 7.

[Byline: Katie Atkins]

