Date: Wed 26 Oct 2016
From: Moisés Vargas-Terán <moisesvargasteran@gmail.com> [edited]


Comments about the event, New World screwworm (NWS) that has occurred in Florida, USA, which are based on ProMED public briefing notes on 18, 20 and 22 Oct 2016:

On 18 Oct 2016 the NWS had been detected in the following additional sites to Big Pine Key where it was detected originally: 1) No Name Keys, 2) Big Torch Key, 3) Middle Torch Key, 4) Cudjoe and 5) Ramrod.

According to information available, NWS sterile flies produced by the Panama plant, United States Commission for the Eradication and Prevention of NWS, were to be released on 11 Oct 2016 by the dispersion on land method. If the occurrence of NWS is to be quickly and efficiently contained, you need to make an effort and use the proven aerial release method of sterile flies, especially because the population most affected is wild animals and sterile flies will have a better distribution over infested areas, which does not occur by the method of land release as access of insects is limited to the availability of roads and release points selected for this purpose.

It is also recommended as a preventive measure the (creation) of biological barriers using NWS sterile flies at strategic locations in the area of the Keys and the mainland, until the occurrence in the affected areas is controlled. The current emergency demands that all human and economic resources are employed now, in order to avoid further negative health and economic impacts.

Notes on 20 and 22 Oct 2016 refer to chemical control efforts to prevent and control seizures in adult NWS in the wild deer population. This is an important control measure associated with intensive field inspection of farm animals and pets. Also the application of physical measures, such as the use of a large number of fly traps for NWS, can be useful, while a communication campaign at the local, state or national levels (providing information) on NWS control. However, it should be noted that the above control measure will help reduce the wild population and its consequences, but not the elimination of the NWS.

Proper use of the technique using sterile insects on this occasion, as in others, is the key to the successful elimination of NWS in Florida, USA.

--
Moisés Vargas-Terán
International Animal Health Specialist
<moisesvargasteran@gmail.com>

[I apologise for probably overloading with 2 similar reports out of Florida but they provide colour and details of the doramectin response and some excellent photographs for those needing material for briefing colleagues and instructing students.

We are always glad to hear from our members and we need to. Moises provided some background on himself: "I would like to inform you that currently my present activity is as International Animal Health Expert, with frequent consultancies for OIE and the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA). I am a retired FAO officer, after 23 years as staff member in Animal Production and Health, 7 years based in Rome and 16 in FAO Regional Office for Latin America and the Caribbean in Santiago, Chile. Concerning to my knowledge and experience in the control and eradication of the New World screwworm (NWS) _Cochliomyia hominivorax_, I spent 16 years participating in the diagnosis, control and NWS successful elimination using the Sterile Insect Technique (SIT) in USA, Mexico, Guatemala and Belize. At FAO Rome I was the technical officer responsible for the NWS eradication in Libya (1988-1991) and the Screwworm Emergency Centre for North Africa (SECNA). Currently I am the Senior Technical Consultant for the IAEA project RLA 5067 for Supporting Capability Building of Feasibility of a Progressive NWS Control in 8 South American countries."

Moises, many thanks. - Mod.MHJ

